title: Prusa i2 Revamp - Cubic Structure Conversion

description.text:
I was unhappy with the standard Prusa i2 design and it's limitation, mainly because when printing an object over 50mm high, the extruder gear would hit the frame if homing the x-axis or near the edges. If you have a similar issue, or want to convert to this, I've been running this conversion for ~9 spools of filament now and it's great. Rod lengths are provided as well, I used standard 5/16" threaded rod from the hardware store. (8mm would work too). There are also files included for a spool holder, which utilizes standard 608 skateboard bearings (2 total), as well as the same 5/16 (or 8mm) threaded rod. -Prusauniversalfoot - QTY 4

title: Drive Gear for Model 17 Pencil Sharpener

description.text: My wife found a Boston Model 17 pencil sharpener missing its shaving tray. After printing a tray (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:672194), the drive gear broke. Looking on line, it seems this is a common failure for this model. I tried printing a gear that others had posted (Thingiverse #267626 & #499349), but my pencil sharpener transitions from the slotted key to a round shaft half-way through the part. After machining the gear to fit, it was too wobbly. This was completely re-drafted using VariCAD and the oblong key and circular shaft are integral to the center cylinder. It also includes an inset on the spring clip side similar to the original gear to make it easier to get the spring clip attached. I've included a separate test piece that is identical to the center cylinder to allow people to scale to fit, you should be able to scale within a few percent and still have everything fit. The test piece prints out fairly quickly and doesn't use much material, so using it to determine by how much to scale the full gear should go pretty quickly. The gear is 1/32" under-size in diameter (1/64" undersize in radius), so you have a little wiggle room to adjust for shrinkage. See the instructions for more detail

I made the gear using Taulman Bridge material. If you use ABS, you may need to adjust scaling for shrinkage Settings were:
0.35 nozzle
240 C extrusion material, 90 C bed using glue stick on the glass
Part was printed on a raft, the gear was printed on a raft with support.
0.2 mm layer height
5 top and 5 bottom layers (I like a thick shell)
75% infill
25 mm/s infill speed
13 mm/s perimeter speed
30 mm/s for support material
40 mm/s for bridges
100 mm/s for non-print moves
First layer speed 80% Print the independent center cylinder to adjust scaling to fit; you should be able to scale within a few percent and still have everything fit. After scaling the center cylinder, you can scale the whole gear the same amount. The gear is 1/32" under-size in diameter (1/64" undersize in radius), so you have a little wiggle room to adjust for shrinkage. If not, you can at least come close -- gear size will be the most important parameter and you will have to live with any issues on the cylinder.

This design doesn't require the extruder to be taken apart like others do.

I printed with %70 infill.
Choose appropriate length fasteners, the screws used to attached top mount on the Z arm may have to be cut down a bit.
The bottom mount use's M5x30mm.
On the bottom mount there is a Hexagonal cut out this is ideally for a 6-8mm M3 stand off.
A stand-off with 5mm Across Flats works perfect, but the more common 5.5mm across flats may need to be heated up and pressed in.
Failing all that you can use a M3 nut.
Some faces may need some filling to fit, depending on your printers accuracy. (mine always prints a little large)

title: ABS print test with Fan on/off

description.text:
Googling around I did not found straight answer how print fan affect ABS prints. So I made calibration figure and printed it out with fan on and off. G-code was modified to change hotend temperature during print.
Conclusion was then using fan hot end temperature should be significantly higher (260 instead of 230). Printing with high temperature and fan on helps for better bridging and keeps layers stronger together.
Probably my conclusions is subjective but this experiment gave me answer I was looking for.

description.text: Edit: Please check out my newest version if you're interested in modding your transmitter

I've been using a GT2B transmitter for my electric longboard, it's a great radio. But in it's original form it's pretty bulky and not very pocket-friendly while you're not using it.  
This case minimizes it and leaves you with just the throttle trigger as the only input channel.

To assemble you'll need; 1 x ~250 mah thin lipo cell (to replace original bulky battery)
2 x 680 ohm resistors (solder where on the inputs to the unused channel)
1 x ON/OFF Switch of your choosing (remember to create a hole in the case for that will fit your switch)
1 x M3 14mm screw (to hold trigger)
1 x M3 4mm screw (PCB)
4 x M3 8mm screws (case halves)
2 x M3 nuts (on the trigger screw between the pcb) Some tips while modding your transmitter;

  • Take your time and be careful when desoldering the USB-jack

  • Cut the bind button and rev-throttle switch short to allow the trigger full movement (or loose 1mm in range)

  • Do a transmitter calibration on your ESC when you're done

description.header: NEW: WATCH THE VIDEO OF HOW CATASTRONAUT WAS CREATED: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KWEL20pHax8
Many tell of the fabled CAPTAIN JONAH: Space adventurer, hero.

description.text: His many daring missions are passed on to each new generation of Space Cadet - each aspiring to be one-tenth of the Cosmonaut the legend of Jonah became...
This model at last depicts the unfortunate demise of the astro-legend, in all of its unlucky glory.

• DESIGNED TO PRINT IN HIGH RES WITH SUPPORTS
  • CREATED FOR MINIMUM 150mm x 150mm PRINT AREA
  • Component parts push together to build the figure
  • Basic moving joints
  • Can be made in 4 colours (suggest Black, Silver, White and Clear)
  • Can also work in one colour
  • Figure can stand alone (Display Stand is optional)
  • Holes built-in for addition of atmospheric mini electric lighting (not included)
  • Air-hose pieces can be configured in many ways for different display

You can learn more at http://www.ishouldreallygetoutmore.com I'm an illustrator and Art Director working in London. I've dabble in using 3D printers at work, but only to run out simple models. This is my first serious attempt at making a custom 3D model kit. It took several months and a lot of learning! It was designed to be built at HIGH RES - I have not tried to print this at low res, so I don't know how the joints will work at that quality. Its designed to be pushed together, and allow for a little posability from the figure. I created it with colours in mind - but ultimately it can be anything you like!. The clear parts ' have to be clear - they can be printed in any colour and it will still work just fine. I created the 3D model using AutoDesk 123D - which is a fantastic program to start learning how to create a 3D model. With its simple tools I was able to make everything you see. When I started designing it, I didn't even have a 3D printer of my own! I used a commercial print company to run off a test model - this was all in one colour, but I wanted to learn how the parts would fit together (or not at all as it turned out for version1!) I learned a lot about how a model may work on-screen, but when you actually make it for real there can be a need for adjustments or different thinking. Later when I eventually got a printer of my own, I learned yet more about the orientation of the model parts and howe that can affect printing. Also supports, and how to get the best out them - hopefully all of my learning should be transferred into the model, and as long as you use SUPPORTS and HIGH RES to print, it should come out just fine when you put it together. But keep some sandpaper and tools to hand! I can't predict how your print may come out, (as I often couldn't for my own) so you may have to expect some fine-tuning. I'll be creating a video showing a little more about how the model came about - you'll be able to find it via my blog at http://www.ishouldreallygetoutmore.com

title: Kongotronic Time Absconder Clock REMIX
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Coming at you to consume all your time, the Time Absconder just doesn't care. Spikes here and spikes there, the Time Absconder likes to rock out. Who puts sunglasses on a robot? Well guess who. You like flying robots? You get some wings, even if you are a clock.  
A 2015 update to Kongorilla's sublime TIme Defender 3000, make yourself a Time Absconder and you too can be cool and successful (or at least know what time it is). You will need to get the un-modded parts -- the connectors, clock mount and dial, the tread mount and the body --  from the original Kongotronic posting (linked over there to the right for the slow ones - while you there consider donating to the guy, as this was his design originally). You can also use one of the original dials if these new ones are just too X-treme for you. The Absconder won't care.

Follow Kongorilla's instructions at the Time Defender post. The arms in this are combined so you will need to clip the hand mount and use the one that prints with the connectors (I use a wood screw so the hands can still rotate). The Time Absconder can't be bothered to pose for you, so you will need to glue his hands in the rock out position if you want to keep that, otherwise you will get the 'Spider-man' hands (which is not such a bad thing).  
If you are like me and you occasionally buy the wrong clock mechanism, this model will support both the correct one, and the long-dial-mount one.

title: E3D V6 3mm Bowden Mount for Taz

description.text:
Mounts the Bowden version of the 3mm V6, by E3D.  
You will probably want all three pieces. The Mount is just a groove mount. The retainer (may be optional), goes between your extruder mount and the groove mount. It reduces the chance of developing wiggle.  
The Extruder body is very important for using the bowden version of the hotend. I preferred to purchase the Bowden version of the hot end, because it will let me run a Bowden tube straight from the hobbed bolt to the heat break inside the V6 (the Bowden v6 comes with the appropriate tubing). This will give no reason for any flexible filaments to buckle or become a problem. The extruder body accommodates the taller upper-portion of the Bowden v6 and the Bowden tubing (you will only need a small portion of what e3d sends in the bowden kit).  
I upgraded a Taz 4 with this. No additional hardware is needed, unless you are building a separate extruder (rather than just disassembling the one you have and salvaging those parts). I have not tried with other Taz printers, as I only own the one. It should certainly work with the Taz 5 though, as I modified the Fangtooth (Taz5) extruder body, to make this one (can be found at               devel.lulzbot.com). You may not even need to print the mount, as I have heard the aluminum mount for the Hexagon hot end fits nicely on the V6

I would recommend layer heights of 0.2mm, since I kept all dimensions to multiples of 0.2.  
I would also NOT recommend PLA, or other low temperature plastics. The V6 stays cool at the cold-end, due to its heat sink and fan, but High-temp plastics will certainly hold up better if your fan stops working. If you print in PLA, print an extra, in case you have a fan failure and you melt something.

Made these to stand the Dishwasher on.
Our Fitted dishwasher within the fitted units has it's feet adjustment screws turned out to nearly their maximum to make it fit so a little unstable.
This raises the feet of the machine up by 40mm, with a total height of 45mm

I'd recommend the walls made at least 3 or 4 layers thick with 4 top and bottom layers. I made with a 15% fill but you may wish to increase this to 30% or more depending upon the weight you wish to support.
I may glue these to the kitchen floor to ensure that it all remains in position. Corners radiused to reduce structural stress. It shouldn't require any supporting structure. Here's a link to the FEMA suggestions for what to put in the pack. http://www.fema.gov/areyouready/assemble_disaster_supplies_kit.shtm If there is too much to fit in the little pack, put it in your own darn pack daddy.:)

You'll need a 25lb rice bag or similar sturdy bag, a cereal box, a little cardboard and some tape.

  • unravel the stitching at the bottom of the bag, and cut along the side so you have a large sheet.

  • Cut the cereal box a little shorter for small kids. I cut approximately 4 inches off the top, leaving a flap on the back to fold over as a lid.

  • Put the box on the sheet and wrap it like a present leaving the top open,and leave the corner flaps at the bottom sticking out for attachment of the shoulder straps. Use sturdy tape and tape the bottom and the front both inside and outside.

  • Cut long strips off the top of the bag for shoulder straps. Make them about 4 inches wide.

  • Put a 8 to 10 inch long, 2 inch wide strip of cardboard on the shoulder strap and fold the strap around the cardboard, and tape it. This provides some padding and prevents the straps from bunching up and cutting into your shoulders.

  • Sew the shoulder straps to the triangle tabs at the bottom and to the top back of the pack just below the top of the box when folded closed.

  • Tape the bottom triangle up along the sides or down to the bottom if desired.

  • Pack it with stuff needed for emergencies. Tape it closed. Store it and forget about it.

description.text: A creature build by AutoDesk Tinker play APP!

Hoping to get a short repose from the frenzied chaos of the race, and to repair his damage, Twonky shut down his systems and went into power down mode. While his cpu was running in standby, he began to experience strange, realistic visions. He was on another factory floor, back in some sort of race. And surrounded by more Twonkys. All were driving around, firing their lasers as they went, bumping into each other. And some where coming his way... I wanted to make a travel version of the game RoboRally by Avalon Hill. A single board is usually 12x12 tiles, but I broke them up into 3x3 tiles. And because everybody wants to play Twonky, there's no need to have other bots. Just lots of Twonkys.
Movement and option cards needed to play the game can be taken from the original game.

Supports:

No

The game board is divided into 3x3 squares. Each is printable without support. Printed, the tiles are just under 2" square, but you can always scale them up and print them full-size if you want.
The tiles with gears on them have tiny arrows, but I painted a bigger white arrow on it to make it more clear.
The individual_tiles.zip contains all the 1x1 separate tiles. I fixed the offset height of the arrows and wrenches in these files as well.
Twonky needs a little support at the bottom front, but gave no trouble printing on my m200. I still have to paint my Twonkys. Or print them with different color filaments.
This is a flag. Hopefully printable without support. Have to try it soon.
The scad files are the source files for the tiles and for Twonky.

The tiles are made up of nine individual tiles. When rotating an individual tile, I get an manifold error when trying to export it to stl. If anyone can fix this, it would be much appreciated. Otherwise, I have to create a rotated module for each tile.

description.text:
This is a project I started some ago (I still had a Prusa i3) and took me some time to finish. Those of us who are close to the 40s, have been always touched by the idea of having a cabinet at home. Those playing machines we used to enjoy with a coin when we were boys. That's because, when I started my first 3d printer, it was something i wanted to develop. It has to be something easy to print, not so big for a home and cheap, so I started my design in blocks. All of these blocks are printable in small printers, then, you just "stich" them with some nuts and screws and the machine comes alive. It's easy, don't be afraid. The "brain" of the machine is a Raspberry Pi B. I don't know if they are easy to find right now with the version 2 at shops, and I don't have a Raspy2, but if someone needs it for a Raspberry 2 I can modify the STL. The LCD is a 7'' chinese display, they are cheap and easy to find, about 20$. Also we are going to need a voltage regulator to drop the current to 5v (Raspberry), a 12v power supply, the joystick (Sanwa Style) and 8 buttons. I use 4 of them for playing, 1 for insert coin, 1 for player start, 1 for ENTER and 1 for SCAPE. Configuration is easy, but if someone needs it I can upload a ISO from the SD. Hope you enjoy!

description.text:
This 3D print requires additional parts. See updated photos on wiring up control switch
Wiring instructions:
  • Brown (-) and Green (+) from the Ultrasonic mister
  • Green wire goes in series with the switch, comes out as the red wire, joins back to the Step Down DC-DC Module (+IN)
  • Brown goes direct to -IN of Step Down module
  • Module has 2 solder holes per input, this make it easy to join the inputs (+IN and -IN) back out to the humidifier (after the switch), the switch simply becomes the ON/OFF control for everything.
  • Adjust to correct voltage (+OUT and -OUT) with your voltmeter
  • Connect +OUT and -OUT to your 30mm 12V DC Fan
  • NOTE: - IN and -OUT are effective the same connection
  • Congratulate yourself, job done!
    • Waterproofing your print, making it watertight
    Always a problem for any prints
  • On Cura, go to Expert menu -> Open expert settings (CTRL-E), increase infill overlap to 50%, try to increase infill, if possible, print 100%
  • With ABS, brush the inside with pure acetone
  • With PLA, brush with clear acrylic, e.g. Tamiya X-22, clear gloss coat*
    • BOM include:
    1) Ultrasonic Atomiser (Search ebay for ultrasonic mist fogger, it's the black plastic version, 36mm diameter)
    2) 30mm Fan (4 x 18mm screw for attachment)
    3) 2 (height) x3 (diameter) mm neodydium magnets (Search ebay)
    4) A Step down power converter module, (http://www.icstation.com/step-down-module-power-supply-p-2734.html)
    5) Rectangle flashlight push button switch (http://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/3-Pcs-Rectangle-Flashlight-Latching-Push-Button-Switch-AC-250V-1-5A-/121759137697?hash=item1c5968ffa1:g:N3UAAOSwEetV9dkz) You can use either a 'coke' PET bottle or Kikkoman Soy Sauce classic bottle (look nicer and it's glass). The ultrasonic atomiser requires 18~24V, you can use any 19V laptop adpater for this purpose, old Dell and Acer's often uses regular 2.5mm DC plug. The fan blower speed can be adjusted with the voltage step down module. The humidifier blower is held in place simply with the magnets superglued into the inserts. Ref: Transient high-frequency ultrasonic water atomization
    F. Barreras, H. Amaveda, A. Lozano
    http://ideafix.litec.csic.es/users/felix/2002-EinF-v33n3.pdf

description.text:
This thing is obsolete. Here is the next generation version: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:7831 This thing is an experimental printable elastomeric coupling designed for a molded and cured-in-place rubber insert. The rubber part is cured-in place RTV silicone sealer. It has robust clamping, and should be well balanced if tightened evenly. Heritage: This is a variation of: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:7678 based on the suggestion there by JelleAtProtospace =================================
AFTER I BUILD AND TEST THIS THING, I THINK IT FAIL. Basically the silicone takes a long time to cure and is too soft. Overloads tend to make it want to go off center. I do not recommend making this thing.

Print the parts. Use a solid profile for strength. Clean up. Run a 3mm drill through the clamping holes. The clamps will have good clamping force, but limited travel. The part should press onto the shafts with some reasonable force. If they are loose on the shafts, please make the shaft hole sizes slightly smaller and re-print. The idea is to fill the cup with RTV silicone sealer, and drop the top piece in. Kind of jiggle it around to work the silicone in all the spaces. edit: Let it cure 24 hours in a warm place (on a heat vent or a sunny window sill). 24 hours was no where near cured. I need to re-think that. Clean off the excess silicone by rubbing, then carefully cut the thin alignment triangles off the top piece. If more flexibility is needed you could carefully remove the thin cylinder of the bottom piece that was used to hold the silicone in place while it cured. Other materials could be used to get other stiffness. Maybe Sho Goo ( http://bit.ly/hc11mc )? If you build this, please feed back what you use and how it works for you -- thanks!

title: Printrbot Simple Metal Fancy Spool Holder

description.text:
Yes, another spool holder for Printrbot Simple Metal...  
I wanted one that was vertical, centered over the bars, compact, sturdy and with little friction. It also had to be simple to use, support large spools and look ok.   
This one accepts spools up to ~90mm wide and 110mm in radius.  
I started with a 32mm PVC pipe I had and used that as the axis. The result is virtually frictionless, the spool actually rotates both ways depending on the motion of the Y-axis. If you don't have a 32 mm PVC pipe, an  equivalent STL file to print is included. press fit end-caps are included for the PVC pipe. There are also adapters for eSUN spools and the 32mm PCV axis, plus rings to keep things centered.  
I made collars for extra rigidity under the main part. Screw holes included for M3 screws. I used these collars in my first printed version (see photo), but this version has closer tolerance, and the collars do not seem to be required. They are included anyway.  
A test piece with bar holes is included so you can print it quickly and check your printers calibration for printing this spool holder. The test piece should fit exactly over the vertical bars as shown, without forcing anything.  
I printed with Cura, eSUN PLA filament, layer height 0.2mm, shell bottom/top thickness 0.8mm, fill density 15%, print speed 70mm/s.

A test piece with bar holes is included so you can print it quickly and check your printers calibration for printing this spool holder. The test piece should fit exactly over the vertical bars as shown, without forcing anything.

comments.text: I have been using this spool holder for about 9 months, it is working just like I intended. It is simply placed on top of the vertical bars of the Simple Metal, the extra collars are not needed. If you want to check the fit, print the test piece first.

title: 0.48 mm calibration part for Solidoodle Press (0.4 mm nozzle diameter) (20 mm height)

description.text: Simple calibration part for 0.4 mm nozzle diameter. Height 20 mm.

If you have a 0.4 mm nozzle, then you should have an 0.48 mm Extrusion Width. Set extrusion multiplier to 1. Simply upload the STL in the program you use for printing and Print. Measure the thickness of the wall. The new extrusion multiplier should be then modified to this:  
New_Ext_Mult=Old_Ext_mult*0.48 / Thickness Measured.
